definition.value: Organizations primarily for asexual people or which otherwise support asexual people.
Organizations primarily for transgender people or which otherwise support transgender people.
Organizations primarily for lesbians or which otherwise support lesbians.
Organizations primarily for gay men or which otherwise support gay men.
Organizations primarily for intersex people or which otherwise support intersex people.
LGBTQIA+ organizations focused on advocacy of LGBTQIA+ persons in medical care and research.
Organizations which support or otherwise advocate for gay liberation.
Any of various procedures that are part of the legal system.
An attempt to avoid criminal or civil liability following allegations in a criminal or civil proceeding.
An attempt to avoid criminal liability following allegations in a criminal proceeding.
A legal defense which provides an admission of guilt with justification that certain factors provide the defendant with lack of criminal intent.

An affirmative defense by excuse in a criminal case, arguing that the defendant is not responsible for his or her actions due to an episodic or persistent psychiatric condition at the time of the criminal act.
An affirmative defense by excuse in a criminal case, arguing that the defendant is not responsible for his or her actions due to a temporary insane state during the commission of a crime.
A temporary insanity defense involving a state of panic.

The gay panic defense is a legal defense, usually against charges of assault or murder. A defendant using the defense claims they acted in a state of violent temporary insanity because of unwanted homosexual advances from another individual. The defendant alleges to find the same-sex sexual advances so offensive and frightening that it brings on a psychotic state characterized by unusual violence.

A panic defense applied in cases of assault, manslaughter, or murder of a transgender individual, with whom the assailant(s) engaged in sexual relations unaware that the victim is transgender until seeing them naked, or further into or after sexual activity.

A movement from within the queer communities described as a radical alternative to gay mainstreaming and directly posits an alternative view of gay pride events and activities which have become increasingly commercialized with corporate sponsors and "safer" agendas to avoid offending supporters and sponsors.

A student-led or community-based organization, found in middle schools and high schools as well as colleges and universities, primarily in the United States and Canada, that is intended to provide a safe and supportive environment for LGBTQIA+ children, teenagers, and youth as well as their cisgender heterosexual allies.
Radical feminist ideologies based upon inclusionary or exclusionary identity criteria.
Sexuality in which a person is principally attracted to themself.
Radical feminist ideologies based upon inclusionary or exclusionary identity criteria regarding lesbians.
Radical feminist ideologies based upon inclusionary or exclusionary identity criteria regarding transgender people, particularly transgender women.

A lesbian movement that challenges the status quo of heterosexuality and mainstream feminism. It arose in part because mainstream feminism did not actively include or fight for lesbian rights. The movement was started by lesbian feminist groups in the United States in the 1950s and 1960s. A Canadian movement followed in the 1970s, which added momentum. As it continued to gain popularity, radical lesbianism spread throughout Canada, the United States, and France.
Radical feminist ideologies based upon inclusionary identity criteria regarding transgender people, specifically transgender women.
Radical feminist ideologies based upon exclusionary identity criteria regarding transgender people, specifically transgender women.
Oftentimes this term is a misnormer applied to conservative anti-feminist anti-gender movements.

A form of radical feminism (although this is highly debated) which purports to be based upon a critical reading or definition of what gender is or is seen to be, thus basing particular criteria on womanhood or what a "real" woman is. Such ideologies are almost always transphobic and used to exclude transgender women from women's spaces, among other things.
Oftentimes this term is a misnormer applied to conservative anti-feminist anti-gender movements.
A profound and persistent happiness related to one's gender.
Such a condition is often reported by persons identifying as transgender following any of various hormone therapies or gender-affirming surgeries.
The "bending" (or changing) of expected gender roles, either in fiction or in real life.

"Genderbend" is sometimes used as a synonym for genderswap, but the two are explicitly differentiated in order to avoid confusion, with one (swapping) referring to fictional characters changing gender, whereas the other (bending) refers to "bending" of expected gender roles in any context, including in real life (sometimes as a form of social activism).
Gender nonconformity which seeks to subvert traditional notions of gender identity, expression, and role; often in a way that may be seen or viewed as offensive by some parties.
A person with a gender identity, expression, and/or role which is considered variant within the sociocultural understandings of gender within which that individual lives.
Note that this definition may include agender persons, which "gendered person" does not.
Any form of language which utilizes a system of grammatical gender which may or may not be tied to forms of gender expression and identity in a given culture that utilizes said language.
Gender-neutral language is language that avoids bias towards a particular sex or social gender.
Note that usage of gender-neutral language does not imply that the language itself is genderless, i.e. has no sense of grammatical gender as a classification for nouns.
Any of various states provided to a person.
A position held by something or someone in regard to the law.
A formal acknowledgment of truth, validity, legality, or worthiness of consideration in a given legal system.
Legal recognition of a person's gender identity and/or expression.
Equitable representation of persons of different genders.

The state of equal ease of access to resources and opportunities regardless of gender, including economic participation and decision-making; and the state of valuing different behaviors, aspirations and needs equally, regardless of gender.

The quality of diverse or different cultures, as opposed to monoculture, the global monoculture, or a homogenization of cultures, akin to cultural decay. The phrase cultural diversity can also refer to having different cultures respect each other's differences. The phrase "cultural diversity" is also sometimes used to mean the variety of human societies or cultures in a specific region, or in the world as a whole.
A term used by some transgender women to refer to their intromittent organ; alternatively, any penile structure feminized due to estrogenic hormones.
A term used to refer to the penis in cisgender men; alternatively, any penile structure masculinized due to androgenic hormones.
A person who falls on the spectrum between asexuality and allosexuality (sexuality).
A person who does not experience sexual attraction to another unless they have formed a specific emotional connection with that person.
A person with a romantic orientation somewhere between aromantic and alloromantic.
A person who is demiromantic.
A collection of data or computer instructions that tell the computer how to work.
A collection of instructions that performs a specific task when executed by a computer.
A program that gives a computer instructions that provide the user with tools to accomplish a task.

A computer program or software application designed to run on a mobile device such as a phone, tablet, or watch. Apps were originally intended for productivity assistance such as email, calendar, and contact databases, but the public demand for apps caused rapid expansion into other areas such as mobile games, factory automation, GPS and location-based services, order-tracking, and ticket purchases, so that there are now millions of apps available.

An online dating service presented through a mobile phone application, often taking advantage of a smartphone's GPS location capabilities, always on-hand presence, and easy access to digital photo galleries and mobile wallets to enhance the traditional nature of online dating.
